summary:
Mucins are defined as heavy molecular weight glycoproteins consisting of an apoprotein scaffold with dense attachment of carbohydrate chains via both N- and O-glycans. This structural feature is confirmed across biological contexts including normal tissue physiology and pathological conditions such as dry eye syndrome, supporting their classification as glycosylated proteins.\boxed{A}

